          "body": "Verses 5-6 deploy one of Isaiah's most carefully constructed agricultural metaphors. The enemy army — almost certainly Assyria in the historical referent, though the oracle's application is broader — is a vine in full growth. The blossom has appeared, the flower has become a ripening grape: the campaign is underway, the forces are fully mobilized, the threat is real. At exactly that moment, the divine vinedresser appears with pruning knives (*mezamerot*, iron curved blades) and cuts off the sprigs, removes the spreading branches. The image is precise because Israel's own covenant identity was as the LORD's vineyard (Isaiah 5:1-7; Psalm 80:8-16). Now the same viticultural action that described Israel's discipline is turned on her enemies: God is the vinedresser of all nations, not Israel's alone. The aftermath of 18:6 — birds of prey in summer, beasts of the earth in harvest — covers two full agricultural seasons, conveying that the judgment is thorough and extended. Peter Davids's observation about James 5 applies equally here: eschatological harvest imagery is never incidental in the prophets; it signals that God's final agricultural accounting is as certain as the season's rotation."
