        "title": "The eschatological reversal — feared Cush at Zion",
        "range": "18:7",
        "excerpt": "At that time a gift of homage will be brought to the LORD of hosts from a people tall and smooth, even from a people feared far and wide, a powerful and oppressive nation, whose land the rivers divide — to the place of the name of the LORD of hosts, even Mount Zion.",
        "body": "Verse 7 is Isaiah 18's eschatological destination, and it resolves the oracle in a way that none of the oracle's opening language predicted. The entire repertoire of Cush's descriptors from 18:2 — tall, smooth, feared, powerful, rivers-divided — is reproduced verbatim. This is not accidental. Isaiah is making the same-nation identification unmistakable: the very people whose diplomatic embassy opened the oracle with a *woe* now appear at Zion bearing tribute.\n\nThe word *shay* (gifts of homage) is lexically rare in the Old Testament, appearing only here and in Psalm 68:29 ('kings will bring gifts to You') and Psalm 76:11 ('let all who are around Him bring gifts to Him who is to be feared'). Both Psalms use *shay* in contexts of the nations presenting tribute to the divine king enthroned at Zion. Isaiah is consciously placing the Cushite tribute in that canonical stream: Cush is not paying a political settlement — they are joining the eschatological procession of nations to Zion prophesied in Isaiah 2:2-4 and Isaiah 60:3-7.\n\nThe destination is named with emphatic specificity: 'the place of the name of the LORD of hosts, even Mount Zion.' *Maqom ha-shem YHWH tsava'ot, Har Tsiyyon* — the Name-theology of Deuteronomy 12 (God causes His name to dwell in the chosen place) is imported into this eschatological moment. Zion is not merely a geographical coordinate but the locus of divine presence, the place where heaven and earth intersect in the Old Testament's spatial theology.\n\nThe oracle's canonical trajectory leads through Isaiah 19:23-25 — where Assyria and Egypt join Israel as 'a blessing in the midst of the earth' — and into Isaiah 60, where 'nations will come to your light, and kings to the brightness of your rising' (60:3), and where Gentile wealth flows to Zion (60:6-7). The Cushites of 18:7 are the first installment of the nations' pilgrimage, a foretaste of the eschatological ingathering that Isaiah will develop throughout the book's second half. Whether one reads 18:7 as fulfilled in the post-exilic return (when Cushites did convert and worship — cf. Zephaniah 3:10, which echoes this verse almost exactly) or as awaiting ultimate fulfillment in the Messianic age, the oracle's direction is clear: the nations' destiny is not military dominance over Judah but worshipping homage before the LORD of hosts.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shay* (gift of homage/tribute) — appearing only here, Psalm 68:29, and Psalm 76:11 in the OT; consistently in contexts of royal tribute brought to the divine king at Zion. *Maqom ha-shem* (place of the name) — the Deuteronomic Name-theology (Deut. 12:5, 11, 21; 14:23-24) that locates divine presence at the chosen sanctuary; Isaiah places the eschatological tribute directly into that covenantal framework. *Tsava'ot* (of hosts) — the divine title that dominates Isaiah 18:7 (appearing twice in one verse), emphasizing that it is the sovereign Lord of all armies — not Cush's, not Assyria's — who receives the homage."
